\details{
For larger grids, precompute shared feature payloads with
\code{\link[=ledgr_precompute_features]{ledgr_precompute_features()}}. When a grid has more than 20 combinations and
\code{precomputed_features = NULL}, ledgr warns because feature computation may be
repeated per candidate.

The result carries row-level \code{execution_seed} and \code{provenance}. Provenance
records what ran, including the candidate feature-set hash; it does not
prove that parameter selection was out-of-sample. The normal discipline is to
sweep on a train snapshot, select a candidate with \code{\link[=ledgr_candidate]{ledgr_candidate()}}, and
evaluate the locked params on a held-out test snapshot with \code{\link[=ledgr_promote]{ledgr_promote()}}
or \code{\link[=ledgr_run]{ledgr_run()}}. Same-snapshot promotion is useful for audit and replay, but
remains in-sample.

Sweep candidate metrics use the experiment's metric context. The returned
table has exactly one sweep-level metric context, available with
\code{ledgr_metric_context(results)}, and promotion context records that source
sweep context separately from the committed run's own metric context.
Candidate warnings, including \code{LEDGR_LAST_BAR_NO_FILL}, are row-level
diagnostics. Inspect them before promotion; committed runs expose their own
result tables and promotion context.
Hash fields in sweep provenance and reproduction keys are summarized in
\link{ledgr_identity_fields}.

Failed candidates are retained as rows when \code{stop_on_error = FALSE}. Contract
errors such as invalid grids, invalid precomputed feature payloads, and Tier 3
strategy preflight failures still abort. Compatibility note: old
feature-factory experiments use a flat parameter-grid contract. Executable
grids with separate \code{feature_params} require active aliases through
\code{ledgr_feature_map()}. Failed rows can be inspected with
\code{ledgr_candidate(..., allow_failed = TRUE)}, but \code{\link[=ledgr_promote]{ledgr_promote()}} rejects
failed candidates. When \code{stop_on_error = TRUE} rethrows a strategy failure,
assert with \code{inherits(e, "ledgr_strategy_error")} rather than exact
class-vector equality.

Parallel sweep interruption is discard-all in v0.1.8.8. If a parallel sweep
is interrupted before all workers return, ledgr stops the worker backend and
throws \code{ledgr_parallel_sweep_interrupted}; no partially promotable sweep
result is returned. Partial-result recovery is intentionally deferred.

Current sweep mode intentionally does not ship automatic ranking,
\code{ledgr_tune()}, per-fold walk-forward PBO, CPCV, DSR, risk-layer insertion,
cost-grid composition, paper/live adapters, intraday-specific support, or
full per-candidate committed-run artifacts. Saved sweeps are compact
candidate evidence, not batches of committed runs.
